04249nam a22005055i 9780773565920DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19961996xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735659207 a10.1515/97807735659202doi  a(DE-B1597)657227  a(OCoLC)1394872127  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1455.R53bA3 1996eb 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a305.42/0921 aRoberts, Barbara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReconstructed World :bA Feminist Biography of Gertrude Richardson /cBarbara Roberts. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1996] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: In Search of Gertie and the Mother-Hearts -- tAbbreviations -- tDestined For “True Womanhood”: Working Class Girlhood, Middle Class Education, Radical Social and Political Milieu (1875-1901) -- tDefeat And Victory: Collapse, Recovery, Respectability (1901-11) -- tNew Destinies: Emigration, Settlement, Farm Wife, and Feminist Leader (1911-14) -- tSisterhood Divided: Suffrage and the War (1914-17) -- t“My Soul Is Going Out from the ‘Women’s Movement’”: The Conscription Issue in Britain and Canada (1915-17) -- tComrades of the New Womanhood: Canada’s Women’s Peace Crusade Versus “The Reign of Force” (1918-19) -- tDespair, Illness, Endurance, Loss, Death – No Happy Endings Here (1920-46) -- tEpilogue: “These Things Were Worth Doing” -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBorn in Leicester, England, and raised in a working-class family, Richardson emigrated to northern Manitoba in 1911. She was influential in the women's and peace movements in both countries. Devoutly religious, she challenged orthodoxy and worked outside the mainstream churches for peace and social justice. She cofounded one of the earliest suffrage groups in Manitoba and was a key activist in peace movements during the Boer War and World War I. She also served as an information centre for international antiwar news and ran an internationally focused women's peace crusade in World War I from her Manitoba farmhouse via the post and newspaper columns. Richardson was also a gifted writer and poet. She wrote on a variety of women's movement issues for British and Canadian newspapers and magazines, including Woman's Century, the magazine of the National Council of Women of Canada. Her outcries against war, her indictment of militarism, and her call for women and men to stand together for justice were powerful messages that still have resonance today. Tragically, poor health, both mental and physical, interfered with Richardson's work and prevented her from achieving the recognition attained by feminist contemporaries such as Nellie McClung.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356592040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773565920423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773565920/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles